{"title_page": "Sue Wagner", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name=Sue Wagner\n|image=\n|alt=\n|caption=\n|order=30th\n|office=Lieutenant Governor of Nevada\n|term_start=January 7, 1991\n|term_end=January 2, 1995\n|governor=Bob Miller \n|predecessor=[[Bob Miller (Nevada governor)|Bob Miller]]\n|successor=[[Lonnie Hammargren]]\n|office2=Member of the [[Nevada Gaming Commission|Gaming Commission of Nevada]]\n|nominator2=[[Bob Miller (Nevada governor)|Bob Miller]]\n|term_start2=1997\n|term_end2=2009\n|predecessor2=\n|successor2=\n|office3 = Member of the [[Nevada Senate]]\n|term_start3 = 1981\n|term_end3 = 1989\n|office4 = Member of the [[Nevada Assembly]]\n|term_start4 = 1975\n|term_end4 = 1980\n|birth_name=Sue Ellen Pooler\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1940|1|6}}\n|birth_place=[[Portland, Maine]]\n|residence=[[Reno, Nevada]]\n|party= formerly [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], currently non-partisan\n}}\n'''Sue Ellen Wagner''' (n\u00e9e '''Pooler'''; January 6, 1940)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=fjQqAAAAYAAJ&q=%22Wagner,+Sue%22+AND+%221940%22&dq=%22Wagner,+Sue%22+AND+%221940%22&hl=en&ei=ad3RTe_NF-be0QHGt5DSCw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CD4Q6AEwAQ]</ref> is an American [[politician]]. She was the 30th [[Lieutenant Governor of Nevada|Lieutenant Governor]] of the U.S. State of [[Nevada]], serving from 1991 to 1995, the first woman to be elected to the position. A moderate who was liberal on social issues, she was a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] until her exit in January 2014 due to the party's shift towards the [[Tea Party movement]].<ref name=leaves>{{cite news | author = Ray Hagar | title = Washoe GOP chairman resigns while former Lt. Gov. Wagner leaves Republican Party | newspaper = Reno Gazette-Journal | publisher = Gannett | date = January 28, 2014 | url = http://blogs.rgj.com/politics/2014/01/28/washoe-gop-chairman-resigns-while-former-lt-gov-wagner-leaves-republican-party/ | archive-url = https://archive.is/20140129170514/http://blogs.rgj.com/politics/2014/01/28/washoe-gop-chairman-resigns-while-former-lt-gov-wagner-leaves-republican-party/ | url-status = dead | archive-date = January 29, 2014 | accessdate = January 29, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nWagner was born Sue Ellen Pooler in [[Portland, Maine]].<ref name=changed>{{cite news | author = Ray Hagar | title = Sue Wagner and the day that changed Nevada politics | newspaper = Reno Gazette-Journal | publisher = Gannett | date = December 29, 2013 | url = http://www.rgj.com/article/20131229/NEWS19/312290028/Sue-Wagner-day-changed-Nevada-politics | accessdate = January 29, 2014 }}</ref> Her father was active in the [[Maine Republican Party]]<ref name=leaves/> until the family moved to [[Tucson, Arizona|Tucson]], [[Arizona]] in 1950, where she grew up.<ref name=changed/><ref name=license>{{cite news | title = License to Steal: Nevada's Gaming Control System in the Megaresort Age | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=AkrSZLf_RF4C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false | accessdate = January 29, 2014 }}</ref> She graduated with a bachelor's degree in political science from the [[University of Arizona]] in 1962 and with a master's degree in history from [[Northwestern University]] in 1963.<ref name=changed/>\n\nShe served as Assistant [[dean of women]] at [[Ohio State University]] from 1963 to 1964, when she married Peter B. Wagner and moved back to Arizona,<ref name=alum>{{cite news | title = 2013 Alum of the Year | newspaper = Catalina High School | url = http://www.catalinahighschoolfoundation.org/about/alumnus-of-the-year/2013-alum-of-the-year/ | accessdate = January 29, 2014 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140203033825/http://www.catalinahighschoolfoundation.org/about/alumnus-of-the-year/2013-alum-of-the-year/ | archive-date = 2014-02-03 | url-status = dead }}</ref> where she worked as a reporter for the [[Tucson Citizen|Tucson Daily Citizen]] from 1964 to 1965. She then worked at [[Catalina Magnet High School|Catalina High School]], teaching government and history from 1965 to 1969 when she, her husband and their two children, Kirk and Kristina, moved to [[Reno, Nevada]].<ref name=records>{{cite news | title = A Guide to the Records of Sue Wagner Collection No. 94-58 | newspaper = University of Nevada, Reno | url = http://knowledgecenter.unr.edu/specoll/mss/94-58.html | date = August 5, 2008 | accessdate = January 29, 2014 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140224161120/http://knowledgecenter.unr.edu/specoll/mss/94-58.html | archivedate = February 24, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n\n===Early political career===\nHer husband, an atmospheric physicist,<ref name=license/> worked as a scientist and associate research professor for the [[Desert Research Institute]] and she became involved in local politics, working on Pat Hardy Lewis' successful campaign for Reno City Council.<ref name=records/> She chaired Reno's Blue Ribbon Task Force on Housing and served on the Mayor's Citizen Advisory Board from 1973 to 1974.<ref name=changed/><ref name=records/>\n\n===Nevada Legislature===\nIn 1974, she was named one of the ten \"Outstanding Young Women in America\" and was elected to the [[Nevada Assembly]],<ref name=changed/><ref name=alum/><ref name=records/> where she served from 1975 to 1980.\n\nThe same year (1980) she was elected to the [[Nevada Senate]] her husband Peter, along with three other Desert Research Institute scientists, was killed in a plane crash in the [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada mountains]].<ref name=records/> Wagner served in the State Senate from 1981 to 1989, chairing the Judiciary Committee for two legislative sessions, the committee through which all gambling-related bills pass.<ref name=license/> During her legislative career, she supported [[women's rights]], helped create a fee on marriage licenses that funded women's shelters, increased funding for public and higher education, supported environmental protections and protections for at-risk children, required tests for infants for metabolic genetic disorders and pushed for increased governmental accountability and ethics reform.<ref name=changed/><ref name=alum/> She was a driving force behind the creation of the [[Nevada Commission on Ethics]] and worked to pass a referendum in 1990 that prohibits the state from amending abortion laws without first winning approval in a referendum.<ref name=alum/><ref name=records/> She is noted for introducing and passing more legislation than any other person in Nevada's history<ref name=alum/> and in 1989 was named one of ten \"Outstanding National Republican Legislators\".<ref name=changed/>\n\n===Lieutenant Governor of Nevada===\nIn 1990, Wagner ran for [[Lieutenant Governor of Nevada]]. In the Republican primary, she received 58,079 votes (75.50%), defeating pro-life activist Charles Frederick \"Andy\" Anderson, who received 11,965 votes (15.55%). The \"[[None of These Candidates]]\" option received 6,887 votes (8.95%).<ref>{{cite news | title = NV Lt. Governor - R Primary | newspaper = Our Campaigns | url = http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=72237 | accessdate = January 29, 2014 }}</ref> In the general election, Wagner faced [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] Jeanne Ireland, the wife of [[University of Nevada, Las Vegas]] [[Athletic director]] [[Bill Ireland]], and won with 173,262 votes (54.57%) to Ireland's 123,889 votes (39.02%). \"None of These Candidates\" received 20,343 votes (6.41%).<ref>{{Cite web|title=NV Lt. Governor Race - Nov 06, 1990 (general Election)|publisher=Our Campaigns|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=71232|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121011170936/http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?SetNow=Y&RaceID=71232|archivedate=11 October 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> She thus became the first woman to be elected to the position, though not the first woman to serve as Lieutenant Governor. [[Maude Frazier]], who had been appointed Lieutenant Governor in 1962 to fill the remaining 6 months of the late [[Rex Bell]]'s term, was the first woman to hold that distinction.<ref name=changed/> The ticket elected in 1990 was a bipartisan one as incumbent Democratic Governor [[Bob Miller (Nevada governor)|Bob Miller]] had been easily re-elected.\n\nWagner had previously been urged by Republican leaders to run for Congress or Governor and had been named as a potential Vice Presidential candidate for [[George H. W. Bush]] in 1988 by the [[National Women's Political Caucus]].<ref name=alum/> With Governor Miller eligible to run for re-election for a second and final term in 1994, Wagner was widely speculated to run in 1998 and was considered to be the frontrunner.<ref name=leaves/><ref name=changed/> However, on [[Labor Day]], September 3, 1990, Wagner was seriously injured in a plane crash just outside the city of [[Fallon, Nevada|Fallon]]. She and Bob Seale, a Republican candidate for State Treasurer, were on their way to [[Carson City, Nevada|Carson City]] from a Labor Day parade and annual Cantaloupe Festival in Fallon when the twin-engined [[Cessna 411]] crashed shortly after takeoff. Seale had been flying the plane, which lost power in the right engine and he was trying to return to the airport when it came down. Wagner and Seale were seriously injured and Seale's wife Judy was killed. Wagner's aide Stephanie Tyler (who served the rest of Wagner's term in the State Senate)<ref name=paths>{{cite news | title = A fateful crash led to many different paths for Nevada politicos | newspaper = Reno Gazette-Journal | url = http://www.rgj.com/article/20131229/NEWS19/312290029/A-fateful-crash-led-many-different-paths-Nevada-politicos | date = December 28, 2013 | accessdate = January 29, 2014 }}</ref> and Seale's campaign manager [[Brian Krolicki]] (a future Lieutenant Governor of Nevada), who were also in the plane, were not seriously injured.<ref>{{cite news | title = 1 Dead, 4 Hurt in Campaign Plane Crash | newspaper = The Los Angeles Times | url = https://articles.latimes.com/1990-09-04/news/mn-700_1_plane-crash | date = September 4, 1990 | accessdate = January 29, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = 2 Nevada state candidates hurt in plane crash | newspaper = The Blade | url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1350&dat=19900904&id=eUVPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=DAMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6892,892707 | date = September 4, 1990 | accessdate = January 29, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nThe crash essentially ended Wagner's elective political career.<ref name=changed/><ref name=paths/> She broke her neck and back, suffered a punctured lung and several broken ribs and had to be placed in a body cast.<ref name=changed/> Regardless, she won the primary and general elections but was still paralyzed when she was sworn-in.<ref name=license/> She went through months of surgery and rehabilitation, suffering from a fusing of several vertebrae and a disease associated with her paralysis.<ref name=license/> Despite this, she was able to effectively serve as lieutenant governor,<ref name=records/> though she did not run for re-election in 1994.<ref name=changed/> That year she was named to the Nevada Women's Fund's Hall of Fame, received a lifetime achievement award from The Capital Women's Political Caucus and was named \"Politician of the Year\" by the Truckee Meadows Human Services Association.<ref name=changed/> Upon leaving office in 1995, she received the Women Executives in State Government's \"Breaking the Glass Ceiling\" Award and became an associate director of the [[Centers, institutes, and facilities related to the University of Nevada, Reno|University of Nevada's Great Basin Policy Research Center]]. Also that year she began teaching political science at the [[University of Nevada, Reno]], mentored girls who were interested in politics and oversaw the [[Nevada Legislature]]'s intern program.<ref name=changed/><ref name=alum/>\n\n===Member of the Nevada Gaming Commission===\nIn 1997, Wagner was appointed to the board of [[Wells Fargo]] bank<ref name=alum/> and in April was named by Governor Miller to the [[Nevada Gaming Commission]].<ref name=changed/> Still suffering from her injuries, Wagner was provided with a special chair and would need to take breaks during some of the 12- and 14-hour-long meetings.<ref name=license/> She saw her role as different from how she had worked as a legislator: \"A legislator seeks compromise, whereas a regulator sees it one way or another. I don't see [being a regulator] as consensus-building. Although, by placing a condition on a license or limit on a license, you could compromise by doing that.\"<ref name=license/> She frequently agreed with the committee's only other female member, Deborah Griffin, and the two were often the dissenting voices in 3\u20132 decisions to give applicants licenses.<ref name=license/> Interested in compulsive gambling, [[Nevada Gaming Control Board]] Chairman Bill Bible appointed her to a statewide committee that considered the problem in 1998.<ref name=license/>\n\n==Retirement==\nWagner retired from the Gaming Commission in 2009 and was awarded the Professional Achievement Award by the University of Arizona Alumni Association.<ref name=changed/> She publicly opposed [[Sharron Angle]], the Republican nominee for the U.S. Senate [[United States Senate election in Nevada, 2010|in 2010]], though she did not endorse Democratic incumbent [[Harry Reid]].<ref name=changed/> In 2013 she was inducted into the Nevada State Senate Hall of Fame. In January 2014 she left the Republican Party, saying: \"I did it as a symbol, I guess, that I do not like the Republican Party and what they stand for today... It's grown so conservative and tea-party orientated and I just can't buy into that. I've left the Republican Party and it's left me, at the same time.\"<ref>{{cite news | title = Former Nevada Lt. Governor Quits GOP | newspaper = Political Wire | url = http://politicalwire.com/archives/2014/01/29/former_nevada_lt_governor_quits_gop.html | date = January 29, 2014 | accessdate = January 29, 2014 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140202093151/http://politicalwire.com/archives/2014/01/29/former_nevada_lt_governor_quits_gop.html | archivedate = February 2, 2014 }}</ref> She currently lives in south-west Reno, supported financially by a settlement from the plane crash.<ref name=changed/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of female lieutenant governors in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://contentdm.library.unr.edu/cgi-bin/showfile.exe?CISOROOT=/unohp&CISOPTR=5131&filename=5132.pdf Through the Glass Ceiling: A Life in Nevada Politics - The oral history of Sue Wagner]{{Dead link|date=June 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}\n*[https://archive.library.unr.edu/public/repositories/2/resources/202 A Guide to the Sue Wagner papers, 94-58]. Special Collections, University Libraries, University of Nevada, Reno.\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-off}}\n{{Succession box|title=[[Lieutenant Governor of Nevada]]|before=[[Bob Miller (Nevada governor)|Bob Miller]]|after=[[Lonnie Hammargren]]|years=January 7, 1991 \u2013 January 2, 1995}}\n{{S-civ}}\n{{S-bef|before=}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Nevada Gaming Commission|Member of the Gaming Commission of Nevada]]|years=1997 \u2013 2009}}\n{{S-aft|rows=2|after=}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Lieutenant Governors of Nevada}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wagner, Sue}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Lieutenant Governors of Nevada]]\n[[Category:Members of the Nevada Assembly]]\n[[Category:Nevada Republicans]]\n[[Category:Nevada state senators]]\n[[Category:Northwestern University alumni]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Portland, Maine]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Reno, Nevada]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Tucson, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Survivors of aviation accidents or incidents]]\n[[Category:University of Arizona alumni]]\n[[Category:Women in Nevada politics]]\n[[Category:Members of American gaming commissions]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name=Sue Wagner\n|image=\n|alt=\n|caption=\n|order=30th\n|office=Lieutenant Governor of Nevada\n|term_start=January 7, 1991\n|term_end=January 2, 1995\n|governor=Bob Miller \n|predecessor=[[Bob Miller (Nevada governor)|Bob Miller]]\n|successor=[[Lonnie Hammargren]]\n|office2=Member of the [[Nevada Gaming Commission|Gaming Commission of Nevada]]\n|nominator2=[[Bob Miller (Nevada governor)|Bob Miller]]\n|term_start2=1997\n|term_end2=2009\n|predecessor2=\n|successor2=\n|office3 = Member of the [[Nevada Senate]]\n|term_start3 = 1981\n|term_end3 = 1989\n|office4 = Member of the [[Nevada Assembly]]\n|term_start4 = 1975\n|term_end4 = 1980\n|birth_name=Sue Ellen Pooler\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1940|1|6}}\n|birth_place=[[Portland, Maine]]\n|residence=[[Reno, Nevada]]\n|party= formerly [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], currently non-partisan\n}}\n'''Sue Ellen Wagner''' (n\u00e9e '''Pooler'''; January 6, 1940)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=fjQqAAAAYAAJ&q=%22Wagner,+Sue%22+AND+%221940%22&dq=%22Wagner,+Sue%22+AND+%221940%22&hl=en&ei=ad3RTe_NF-be0QHGt5DSCw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CD4Q6AEwAQ]</ref> is an American [[politician]]. She was the 30th [[Lieutenant Governor of Nevada|Lieutenant Governor]] of the U.S. State of [[Nevada]], serving from 1991 to 1995, the first woman to be elected to the position. A moderate who was liberal on social issues, she was a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] until her exit in January 2014 due to the party's shift towards the [[Tea Party movement]].<ref name=leaves>{{cite news | author = Ray Hagar | title = Washoe GOP chairman resigns while former Lt. Gov. Wagner leaves Republican Party | newspaper = Reno Gazette-Journal | publisher = Gannett | date = January 28, 2014 | url = http://blogs.rgj.com/politics/2014/01/28/washoe-gop-chairman-resigns-while-former-lt-gov-wagner-leaves-republican-party/ | archive-url = https://archive.is/20140129170514/http://blogs.rgj.com/politics/2014/01/28/washoe-gop-chairman-resigns-while-former-lt-gov-wagner-leaves-republican-party/ | url-status = dead | archive-date = January 29, 2014 | accessdate = January 29, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nWagner was born Sue Ellen Pooler in [[Portland, Maine]].<ref name=changed>{{cite news | author = Ray Hagar | title = Sue Wagner and the day that changed Nevada politics | newspaper = Reno Gazette-Journal | publisher = Gannett | date = December 29, 2013 | url = http://www.rgj.com/article/20131229/NEWS19/312290028/Sue-Wagner-day-changed-Nevada-politics | accessdate = January 29, 2014 }}</ref> Her father was active in the [[Maine Republican Party]]<ref name=leaves/> until the family moved to [[Tucson, Arizona|Tucson]], [[Arizona]] in 1950, where she grew up.<ref name=changed/><ref name=license>{{cite news | title = License to Steal: Nevada's Gaming Control System in the Megaresort Age | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=AkrSZLf_RF4C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false | accessdate = January 29, 2014 }}</ref> She graduated with a bachelor's degree in political science from the [[University of Arizona]] in 1962 and with a master's degree in history from [[Northwestern University]] in 1963.<ref name=changed/>\n\nShe served as Assistant [[dean of women]] at [[Ohio State University]] from 1963 to 1964, when she married Peter B. Wagner and moved back to Arizona,<ref name=alum>{{cite news | title = 2013 Alum of the Year | newspaper = Catalina High School | url = http://www.catalinahighschoolfoundation.org/about/alumnus-of-the-year/2013-alum-of-the-year/ | accessdate = January 29, 2014 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140203033825/http://www.catalinahighschoolfoundation.org/about/alumnus-of-the-year/2013-alum-of-the-year/ | archive-date = 2014-02-03 | url-status = dead }}</ref> where she worked as a reporter for the [[Tucson Citizen|Tucson Daily Citizen]] from 1964 to 1965. She then worked at [[Catalina Magnet High School|Catalina High School]], teaching government and history from 1965 to 1969 when she, her husband and their two children, Kirk and Kristina, moved to [[Reno, Nevada]].<ref name=records>{{cite news | title = A Guide to the Records of Sue Wagner Collection No. 94-58 | newspaper = University of Nevada, Reno | url = http://knowledgecenter.unr.edu/specoll/mss/94-58.html | date = August 5, 2008 | accessdate = January 29, 2014 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140224161120/http://knowledgecenter.unr.edu/specoll/mss/94-58.html | archivedate = February 24, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n\n===Early political career===\nHer husband, an atmospheric physicist,<ref name=license/> worked as a scientist and associate research professor for the [[Desert Research Institute]] and she became involved in local politics, working on Pat Hardy Lewis' successful campaign for Reno City Council.<ref name=records/> She chaired Reno's Blue Ribbon Task Force on Housing and served on the Mayor's Citizen Advisory Board from 1973 to 1974.<ref name=changed/><ref name=records/>\n\n===Nevada Legislature===\nIn 1974, she was named one of the ten \"Outstanding Young Women in America\" and was elected to the [[Nevada Assembly]],<ref name=changed/><ref name=alum/><ref name=records/> where she served from 1975 to 1980.\n\nThe same year (1980) she was elected to the [[Nevada Senate]] her husband Peter, along with three other Desert Research Institute scientists, was killed in a plane crash in the [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada mountains]].<ref name=records/> Wagner served in the State Senate from 1981 to 1989, chairing the Judiciary Committee for two legislative sessions, the committee through which all gambling-related bills pass.<ref name=license/> During her legislative career, she supported [[women's rights]], helped create a fee on marriage licenses that funded women's shelters, increased funding for public and higher education, supported environmental protections and protections for at-risk children, required tests for infants for metabolic genetic disorders and pushed for increased governmental accountability and ethics reform.<ref name=changed/><ref name=alum/> She was a driving force behind the creation of the [[Nevada Commission on Ethics]] and worked to pass a referendum in 1990 that prohibits the state from amending abortion laws without first winning approval in a referendum.<ref name=alum/><ref name=records/> She is noted for introducing and passing more legislation than any other person in Nevada's history<ref name=alum/> and in 1989 was named one of ten \"Outstanding National Republican Legislators\".<ref name=changed/>\n\n===Lieutenant Governor of Nevada===\nIn 1990, Wagner ran for [[Lieutenant Governor of Nevada]]. In the Republican primary, she received 58,079 votes (75.50%), defeating pro-life activist Charles Frederick \"Andy\" Anderson, who received 11,965 votes (15.55%). The \"[[None of These Candidates]]\" option received 6,887 votes (8.95%).<ref>{{cite news | title = NV Lt. Governor - R Primary | newspaper = Our Campaigns | url = http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=72237 | accessdate = January 29, 2014 }}</ref> In the general election, Wagner faced [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] Jeanne Ireland, the wife of [[University of Nevada, Las Vegas]] [[Athletic director]] [[Bill Ireland]], and won with 173,262 votes (54.57%) to Ireland's 123,889 votes (39.02%). \"None of These Candidates\" received 20,343 votes (6.41%).<ref>{{Cite web|title=NV Lt. Governor Race - Nov 06, 1990 (general Election)|publisher=Our Campaigns|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=71232|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121011170936/http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?SetNow=Y&RaceID=71232|archivedate=11 October 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> She thus became the first woman to be elected to the position, though not the first woman to serve as Lieutenant Governor. [[Maude Frazier]], who had been appointed Lieutenant Governor in 1962 to fill the remaining 6 months of the late [[Rex Bell]]'s term, was the first woman to hold that distinction.<ref name=changed/> The ticket elected in 1990 was a bipartisan one as incumbent Democratic Governor [[Bob Miller (Nevada governor)|Bob Miller]] had been easily re-elected.\n\nWagner had previously been urged by Republican leaders to run for Congress or Governor and had been named as a potential Vice Presidential candidate for [[George H. W. Bush]] in 1988 by the [[National Women's Political Caucus]].<ref name=alum/> With Governor Miller eligible to run for re-election for a second and final term in 1994, Wagner was widely speculated to run in 1998 and was considered to be the frontrunner.<ref name=leaves/><ref name=changed/> However, on [[Labor Day]], September 3, 1990, Wagner was seriously injured in a plane crash just outside the city of [[Fallon, Nevada|Fallon]]. She and Bob Seale, a Republican candidate for State Treasurer, were on their way to [[Carson City, Nevada|Carson City]] from a Labor Day parade and annual Cantaloupe Festival in Fallon when the twin-engined [[Cessna 411]] crashed shortly after takeoff. Seale had been flying the plane, which lost power in the right engine and he was trying to return to the airport when it came down. Wagner and Seale were seriously injured and Seale's wife Judy was killed. Wagner's aide Stephanie Tyler (who served the rest of Wagner's term in the State Senate)<ref name=paths>{{cite news | title = A fateful crash led to many different paths for Nevada politicos | newspaper = Reno Gazette-Journal | url = http://www.rgj.com/article/20131229/NEWS19/312290029/A-fateful-crash-led-many-different-paths-Nevada-politicos | date = December 28, 2013 | accessdate = January 29, 2014 }}</ref> and Seale's campaign manager [[Brian Krolicki]] (a future Lieutenant Governor of Nevada), who were also in the plane, were not seriously injured.<ref>{{cite news | title = 1 Dead, 4 Hurt in Campaign Plane Crash | newspaper = The Los Angeles Times | url = https://articles.latimes.com/1990-09-04/news/mn-700_1_plane-crash | date = September 4, 1990 | accessdate = January 29, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = 2 Nevada state candidates hurt in plane crash | newspaper = The Blade | url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1350&dat=19900904&id=eUVPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=DAMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6892,892707 | date = September 4, 1990 | accessdate = January 29, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nThe crash essentially ended Wagner's elective political career.<ref name=changed/><ref name=paths/> She broke her neck and back, suffered a punctured lung and several broken ribs and had to be placed in a body cast.<ref name=changed/> Regardless, she won the primary and general elections but was still paralyzed when she was sworn-in.<ref name=license/> She went through months of surgery and rehabilitation, suffering from a fusing of several vertebrae and a disease associated with her paralysis.<ref name=license/> Despite this, she was able to effectively serve as lieutenant governor,<ref name=records/> though she did not run for re-election in 1994.<ref name=changed/> That year she was named to the Nevada Women's Fund's Hall of Fame, received a lifetime achievement award from The Capital Women's Political Caucus and was named \"Politician of the Year\" by the Truckee Meadows Human Services Association.<ref name=changed/> Upon leaving office in 1995, she received the Women Executives in State Government's \"Breaking the Glass Ceiling\" Award and became an associate director of the [[Centers, institutes, and facilities related to the University of Nevada, Reno|University of Nevada's Great Basin Policy Research Center]]. Also that year she began teaching political science at the [[University of Nevada, Reno]], mentored girls who were interested in politics and oversaw the [[Nevada Legislature]]'s intern program.<ref name=changed/><ref name=alum/>\n\n===Member of the Nevada Gaming Commission===\nIn 1997, Wagner was appointed to the board of [[Wells Fargo]] bank<ref name=alum/> and in April was named by Governor Miller to the [[Nevada Gaming Commission]].<ref name=changed/> Still suffering from her injuries, Wagner was provided with a special chair and would need to take breaks during some of the 12- and 14-hour-long meetings.<ref name=license/> She saw her role as different from how she had worked as a legislator: \"A legislator seeks compromise, whereas a regulator sees it one way or another. I don't see [being a regulator] as consensus-building. Although, by placing a condition on a license or limit on a license, you could compromise by doing that.\"<ref name=license/> She frequently agreed with the committee's only other female member, Deborah Griffin, and the two were often the dissenting voices in 3\u20132 decisions to give applicants licenses.<ref name=license/> Interested in compulsive gambling, [[Nevada Gaming Control Board]] Chairman Bill Bible appointed her to a statewide committee that considered the problem in 1998.<ref name=license/>\n\n==Retirement==\nWagner retired from the Gaming Commission in 2009 and was awarded the Professional Achievement Award by the University of Arizona Alumni Association.<ref name=changed/> She publicly opposed [[Sharron Angle]], the Republican nominee for the U.S. Senate [[United States Senate election in Nevada, 2010|in 2010]], though she did not endorse Democratic incumbent [[Harry Reid]].<ref name=changed/> In 2013 she was inducted into the Nevada State Senate Hall of Fame. In January 2014 she left the Republican Party, saying: \"I did it as a symbol, I guess, that I do not like the Republican Party and what they stand for today... It's grown so conservative and tea-party orientated and I just can't buy into that. I've left the Republican Party and it's left me, at the same time.\"<ref>{{cite news | title = Former Nevada Lt. Governor Quits GOP | newspaper = Political Wire | url = http://politicalwire.com/archives/2014/01/29/former_nevada_lt_governor_quits_gop.html | date = January 29, 2014 | accessdate = January 29, 2014 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140202093151/http://politicalwire.com/archives/2014/01/29/former_nevada_lt_governor_quits_gop.html | archivedate = February 2, 2014 }}</ref> She currently lives in south-west Reno, supported financially by a settlement from the plane crash.<ref name=changed/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of female lieutenant governors in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://contentdm.library.unr.edu/cgi-bin/showfile.exe?CISOROOT=/unohp&CISOPTR=5131&filename=5132.pdf Through the Glass Ceiling: A Life in Nevada Politics - The oral history of Sue Wagner]{{Dead link|date=June 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}\n*[http://dewey.library.unr.edu/xtf/view?docId=ead/94-58-ead.xml A Guide to the Sue Wagner papers, 94-58]. Special Collections, University Libraries, University of Nevada, Reno.\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-off}}\n{{Succession box|title=[[Lieutenant Governor of Nevada]]|before=[[Bob Miller (Nevada governor)|Bob Miller]]|after=[[Lonnie Hammargren]]|years=January 7, 1991 \u2013 January 2, 1995}}\n{{S-civ}}\n{{S-bef|before=}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Nevada Gaming Commission|Member of the Gaming Commission of Nevada]]|years=1997 \u2013 2009}}\n{{S-aft|rows=2|after=}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Lieutenant Governors of Nevada}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wagner, Sue}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Lieutenant Governors of Nevada]]\n[[Category:Members of the Nevada Assembly]]\n[[Category:Nevada Republicans]]\n[[Category:Nevada state senators]]\n[[Category:Northwestern University alumni]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Portland, Maine]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Reno, Nevada]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Tucson, Arizona]]